Extract matched groups from a string.

Vectorised over string and pattern.

str_match(string, pattern)

str_match_all(string, pattern)

Arguments

string
Input vector. Either a character vector, or something coercible to one.
pattern
Pattern to look for, as defined by an ICU regular expression. See stringi-search-regex for more details.

Value

For str_match, a character matrix. First column is the complete match, followed by one column for each capture group. For str_match_all, a list of character matrices.

See also

str_extract to extract the complete match, stri_match for the underlying implementation.

Examples

strings <- c(" 219 733 8965", "329-293-8753 ", "banana", "595 794 7569",
  "387 287 6718", "apple", "233.398.9187  ", "482 952 3315",
  "239 923 8115 and 842 566 4692", "Work: 579-499-7527", "$1000",
  "Home: 543.355.3679")
phone <- "([2-9][0-9]{2})[- .]([0-9]{3})[- .]([0-9]{4})"

str_extract(strings, phone)


 [1] "219 733 8965" "329-293-8753" NA             "595 794 7569" "387 287 6718" NA             "233.398.9187"
 [8] "482 952 3315" "239 923 8115" "579-499-7527" NA             "543.355.3679"

x <- c("<a> <b>", "<a> <>", "<a>", "", NA)
str_match(x, "<(.*?)> <(.*?)>")


     [,1]      [,2] [,3]

[2,] "<a> <>"  "a"  ""

[5,] NA        NA   NA
